# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: catholic-church-in-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] A nationwide census, known as **Census 2001**, was conducted in the United Kingdom on Sunday, 29 April 2001.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This was the 20th UK census and recorded a resident population of 58,789,194.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The 2001 UK census was organised by the Office for National Statistics (ONS) in England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Detailed results by region, council area, ward and output area are available from their respective websites.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Similar to previous UK censuses, the 2001 census was organised by the three statistical agencies, ONS, GROS, and NISRA, and coordinated at the national level by the Office for National Statistics.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The Orders in Council to conduct the census, specifying the people and information to be included in the census, were made under the authority of the Census Act 1920 in Great Britain, and the Census Act (Northern Ireland) 1969 in Northern Ireland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In England and Wales these regulations were made by the Census Order 2000 (SI 744/2000), in Scotland by the Census (Scotland) Order 2000 (SSI 68/2000), and in Northern Ireland by the Census Order (Northern Ireland) 2000 (SRNI 168/2000).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The census was administered through self-completion forms, in most cases delivered by enumerators to households and communal establishments in the three weeks before census night on 29 April.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] For the first time return by post was used as the main collection method, with enumerators following up in person where the forms were not returned.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The postal response rate was 88% in England and Wales, 91% in Scotland, and 92% in Northern Ireland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] A total of 81,000 field staff were employed across the UK (70,000 in England and Wales, 8,000 in Scotland and 3,000 in Northern Ireland).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The census was conducted at the height of the foot-and-mouth crisis, which led to extra precautions being adopted by the field staff, and suggestions that the census may have to be postponed.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] However, it was reported that the disease outbreak did not affect the effectiveness of the collection process.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The census was estimated to cost £259m over its 13-year cycle from the start of planning in 1993 to the delivery of final results in 2006.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Printing of the 30 million census forms was subcontracted to Polestar Group, and processing of the returned census forms was subcontracted to Lockheed Martin in a contract worth £54m.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The forms were initially scanned into digital format, then read with OMR and OCR, with manual entry where the automatic process could not read the forms.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The forms were then pulped and recycled, and the digital copies printed onto microfilm for storage and release after 100 years.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Once the data were returned to the statistics agencies it underwent further processing to ensure consistency and to impute missing values.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The overall response rate for the census, that is the proportion of the population who were included on a census form, was estimated to be 94% in England and Wales, 96.1% in Scotland and 95.2% in Northern Ireland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This was due to a number of factors: households with no response, households excluding residents from their returns, and addresses not included in the enumeration.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In Manchester for example 25,000 people from 14,000 addresses were not enumerated because the address database was two years out of date.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The Local Authority with the lowest response was Kensington and Chelsea with 64%.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Hackney had the next lowest response at 72%.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Out of all local authorities, the ten lowest response rates were all in London.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The results still represent 100 per cent of the population, however, because some individuals not completing their forms were instead identified by census enumerators, and through the use of cross-matching with a follow-up survey.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The results from the 2001 census were produced using a methodology known as the One Number Census.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This was an attempt to adjust the census counts and impute answers to allow for estimated under-enumeration measured by the Census Coverage Survey (sample size 320,000 households), resulting in a single set of population estimates.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Although the 1851 census had included a question about religion on a separate response sheet, whose completion was not compulsory, the 2001 census was the first in Great Britain to ask about the religion of respondents on the main census form.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] An amendment to the 1920 Census Act (the Census (Amendment) Act 2000) was passed by Parliament to allow the question to be asked, and to allow the response to this question to be optional.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The inclusion of the question enabled the Jedi census phenomenon to take place in the United Kingdom.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In England and Wales 390,127 people stated their religion as Jedi, as did 14,052 people in Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] 15% declared themselves of no religion (including Jedi at 0.7%, more than those who declared themselves as Sikh, Jewish or Buddhist) and 8% did not respond to the question.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Since the UK census relies on self-completion, the composition of the other ethnic group category is not fixed.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Analysis by the Office for National Statistics of the 220,000 people in England and Wales who ticked the other ethnic group box in the 2001 census reveals that 53 per cent were born in the Far East, 10 per cent in the UK, 10 per cent in the Middle East, and 7 per cent in Africa.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] People could write in an ethnic group under the 'other' heading.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] 26 per cent did not specify an ethnicity, but of the remainder 23 per cent wrote Filipino, 21 per cent Japanese, 11 per cent Vietnamese, 11 per cent Arab, 6 per cent Middle Eastern and 4 per cent North African.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Controversy surrounding the classification of ethnic groups began as early as 2000, when it was revealed that respondents in Scotland and Northern Ireland would be able to check a box describing themselves as Scottish or Irish, an option not available for English respondents.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] With an absence of an English tick-box, the only other tickbox available was "white-British", "Irish", or "other".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] However, if 'English' was written in under the "any other white background" it was not clear whether it would be counted as an ethnic group in same the way as the Welsh.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Following criticism, English was included as a tick-box option in the 2011 census.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] It is sometimes claimed that the 2001 census revealed that two-thirds of the population of Wales described themselves as of Welsh nationality.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In fact, the 2001 census did not collect any information on nationality.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Controversy surrounding the classification of ethnic group began as early as 2000, when it was revealed that respondents in Scotland and Northern Ireland would be able to check a box describing themselves as Scottish or Irish, an option not available for Welsh respondents.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Prior to the census, *Plaid Cymru* backed a petition calling for the inclusion of a Welsh tickbox and for the National Assembly for Wales to have primary law-making powers and its own National Statistics Office.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] With an absence of a Welsh tickbox, the only other tickbox available was "white-British", "Irish", or "other".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] For the first time in a UK census, those wishing to describe their ethnicity as Cornish were given their own code number (06) on the 2001 UK census form, alongside those for people wishing to describe themselves as English, Welsh, Irish or Scottish.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] About 34,000 people in Cornwall and 3,500 people in the rest of the UK wrote on their census forms in 2001 that they considered their ethnic group to be Cornish.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This represented nearly 7% of the population of Cornwall.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Various Cornish organisations were campaigning for the inclusion of the Cornish tick box on the next census in 2011.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A census of the population of the United Kingdom is taken every ten years.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The **2011 census** was held in all countries of the UK on 27 March 2011.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It was the first UK census which could be completed online via the Internet.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics (ONS) is responsible for the census in England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) is responsible for the census in Scotland, and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) is responsible for the census in Northern Ireland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is the executive office of the UK Statistics Authority, a non-ministerial department formed in 2008 and which reports directly to Parliament.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS is the UK Government's single largest statistical producer of independent statistics on the UK's economy and society, used to assist the planning and allocation of resources, policy-making and decision-making.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS designs, manages and runs the census in England and Wales.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In its capacity as the national statistics office for the United Kingdom, ONS also compiles and releases census tables for the United Kingdom when the data from England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland are complete.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In the run-up to the census both the main UK political parties expressed concerns about the increasing cost and the value for money of the census, and it was suggested that the 2011 census might be the last decennial census to be taken.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results from the 2011 census, age and sex, and occupied households estimates for England and Wales and Northern Ireland, were released on 16 July 2012.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results for Scotland, and the first UK-wide results, were published on 17 December 2012.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed and specialised data were published from 2013.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Registrar General John Rickman conducted the first census of Great Britain's population, and was responsible for the ten-yearly reports published between 1801 and 1831.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the first 100 years of census-taking the population of England and Wales grew more than threefold, to around 32 million, and that of Scotland, where a separate census has been carried out since 1861, to about 4.5 million.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 1911 onwards rapid social change, scientific breakthroughs, and major world events affected the structure of the population.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A fire that destroyed census records in 1931, and the declaration of war in 1939, made the 1951 census hugely significant in recording 30 years of change over one of the most turbulent periods in British history.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 1971 census was run by the newly created Office of Population Censuses and Surveys (OPCS), a body formed by the merger of the General Register Office and Government Social Survey.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 1996 the Office for National Statistics (ONS) was formed by merging the Central Statistical Office (CSO), OPCS and the statistics division of the Department of Employment; the first census it ran was in 2001.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2008 the UK Statistics Authority was established as an independent body.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A population census is a key instrument for assessing the needs of local communities.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] When related to other data sources such as housing or agricultural censuses, or sample surveys, the data becomes even more useful.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Most countries of the world take censuses: the United Nations recommends that countries take a census at least once every ten years.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Twenty-one out of 40 countries in Europe are engaged in the 2010–2011 census round The design for the 2011 census reflected changes in society since 2001 and asked questions to help paint a detailed demographic picture of England and Wales, as it stood on census day, 27 March 2011.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Data collected by the census is used to provide statistical outputs which central government uses to plan and allocate local authority services funding, and which local authorities themselves use to identify and meet the needs of their local communities.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Other organisations that use census data include healthcare organisations, community groups, researchers and businesses.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questionnaires, including people's personal information, are kept confidential for 100 years before being released to the public, providing an important source of information for historical, demographic and genealogy research.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for England and Wales included around 25 million households.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] People could complete and submit their questionnaire online, or fill it in on paper and post it back in a pre-addressed envelope.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Guidance was provided online and through the census helpline.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Completed questionnaires were electronically tracked and field staff followed up with households that did not return a questionnaire.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In these cases field staff delivered and collected questionnaires and, where needed, provided advice or assistance in completing the questionnaire.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] There was a legal requirement to complete the 2011 census questionnaire, under the terms of the Census Act 1920.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] As at 27 March 2011 everyone who had lived or intended to live in the country for three months or more was required to complete a questionnaire.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Failure to return a completed questionnaire could lead to a fine and criminal record.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Lockheed Martin UK, the UK arm of US-based aerospace, defence, security, and technology company Lockheed Martin was awarded the contract to provide services for the census comprising questionnaire printing, a customer contact centre and data capture and processing.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The contract was valued at £150 million, approximately one third of the total £482 million census budget.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Concerns were raised during contract negotiations that the US PATRIOT Act could be used to force Lockheed Martin to reveal census data to US authorities.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several groups called for a boycott of the census over the involvement of Lockheed Martin, including the Stop the War Coalition, and the Christian thinktank Ekklesia.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The groups were concerned about sharing data with a company involved in surveillance and data processing for the CIA and FBI; and also providing funding to an arms company making nuclear missiles and cluster bombs.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Green Party also objected, and campaigned unsuccessfully to stop Lockheed Martin getting the contract, although no decision was made about whether or not to call for a boycott.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Census Alert campaign group also decided against calling for a boycott.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy said a boycott would be counter-productive, as the census is used to distribute funding to local services.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy reports that a council may lose £22,000 over 10 years for each person who does not complete the census.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The census for England and Wales was trialled in 135,000 households in Lancaster, the London Borough of Newham and Anglesey on 11 October 2009.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A test was also carried out in Birmingham at the same time.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questions for the 2011 census were the same as those trialled in the 2009 Census Rehearsal.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Order for the 2011 Census (including the proposed question topics, census date and who should complete the questionnaire) was laid before Parliament in October 2009 and was approved by Parliament and became law in December 2009.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Capita Group was contracted by ONS to recruit, train and administer the pay for the 35,000 temporary ONS workers who worked as field staff for the 2011 census.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The total cost of the 2011 census in England and Wales over the period from 2004/05 to 2015/16 is estimated to be £482 million.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This is more than twice the £210m spent on the 2001 census.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This breaks down to a cost of 87 pence per person, per year (over the life of the census – ten years).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] "The cost equates to about 87p a year per person, demonstrating excellent value for money.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The per capita costs in the UK are less than for many other European countries that carry out similar censuses.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In summary, this census will meet crucial requirements for statistical information that Government and others cannot do without." Minister of State, Cabinet Office (Angela E.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Both the main UK political parties had expressed concerns about the rising costs and value of a ten-yearly census, and on coming into office the UK coalition government had gone as far as suggesting that the 2011 census might be the last of its kind.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In July 2010 the UK government asked ONS to explore other methods of measuring the population.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 the three national statistics bodies, ONS, GROS and NISRA set up a co-ordinated research project known as Beyond 2011.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The project reported its findings in March 2014 and recommended that a UK-wide census in 2021 should take place, and that better use should be made of other demographic data sources.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The general style of the questionnaire was similar to that of the 2001 census.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A rehearsal questionnaire was released in 2009.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several new identity and status options were included for the first time.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2001 only 38 people were reported to have been prosecuted for refusing to complete a questionnaire.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 those who refused to complete the census questionnaire or included false information could face a fine of up to £1,000.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A team of compliance staff were recruited to follow up by visiting those householders who refused to complete a questionnaire or where their questionnaire was not returned or completed correctly.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Advertising promoted the notion of how the UK 2011 census would help to shape Britain's future in areas such as healthcare and education.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] TV adverts, for example, depicted Origami, in census colours, forming objects including school computers and buses.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A short sentence under the census logo informed the viewer that the census was a duty that must be undertaken.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 7 April 2011 advertising focused on reminding people to complete and return by post or submit online.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A question about the number of bedrooms a household has, as well as the names, gender and birth dates of any overnight guests was criticised as "bedroom snooping" by the Conservative Party in opposition.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Although some 37,000 people recorded their identity as Cornish by manually writing it on the form in the 2001 census, no tick-box was provided in 2011 to select Cornish as a White British national identity, despite campaigns.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] As a consequence, posters were created by the census organisation and Cornwall Council which advised residents of how they could identify themselves as Cornish by writing it in the ethnicity, national identity and main language sections.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, people could record Cornwall as their country of birth.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the consultation on the 2011 census the British Humanist Association raised several concerns about question 20, "What is your religion?".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA argued it was a leading question, and suggested that it should be phrased as two questions, "Do you have a religion?" and "If so, what is it?".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It contended that by placing the religion question near the ethnicity question it would encourage some responders to associate religion with cultural identity.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA also ran adverts during March 2011 encouraging the use of the 'no religion' box in the questionnaire.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland had 59 questions in total.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] 14 were about the household and its accommodation and 45 questions were for each individual member of the household to complete.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The rehearsal was held on Sunday 11 October 2009 in two areas, Derriaghy and Moy & Benburb, covering approximately 5,000 households.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland costing around £21.8 million over the six-year period 2008–2014.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Over the ten-year cycle the cost is expected to be about £25 million.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, a wholly owned subsidiary of information technology company CACI was contracted to gather information.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] CACI "provided interrogators who worked at Abu Ghraib prison at the height of the prisoner abuse scandal".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 Scotland census asked 13 household questions and up to 35 questions for each individual.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Plans were rehearsed in west Edinburgh and Lewis and Harris.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census was the first to include a question asking about the ability to read, write and understand the Scots language alongside the question for ability in Scottish Gaelic and English languages.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Responsibility for the release of data from the 2011 census is split between the Office for National Statistics (ONS) for England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) for Scotland and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The ONS announced in March the release plan for the results of the 2011 census which stated in July 2012.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA made a similar announcement with identical release plan.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In June 2012 GROS advised on its release plan which commences in December 2012.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The releases will comprise data sets enabling the standard comparison with previous census data reports as well as over a hundred new data sets based on the new questions asked in the 2011 census.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA, ONS and GROS each publish a schedule stating what documents they will release and when.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Those documents are called a "prospectus".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each prospectus is not fixed, but changes as schedules are changed or documents are late.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The prospectuses are linked to in the table below.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is responsible for publishing United Kingdom wide 2011 census data.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] These are co-ordinated releases coinciding with data published by the three national statistical authorities.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population data including data for males and females for the United Kingdom and revised estimates England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population numbers (rounded), by five-year age bands, sex and densities and household sata at national and local authority level.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates (unrounded) by single year of age and sex for the UK and all local authorities (or equivalent) in the UK, along with UK historic population pyramids (1951–2011).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 1 – Census Profiles; Population, People and Places, Health and Social Care, Travel and Transport.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] National and Local Authority geographies.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 2 – Census Profiles; Qualifications and Labour Market.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 3 – Multivariate, Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for: Living arrangements; Household composition; and Accommodation type.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A series of further releases, subsequent to the four main releases of 2011 Census statistics including migration tables, workplace tables, detailed religion and ethnic group tables, and statistics relating to alternative population bases.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Specialist products would include:- Small population groups; microdata; flow data (also known as origin-destination statistics).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It is also suggested that data organised around alternative population bases may be produced.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The original plans of the ONS, covering England and Wales, confirmed that there would be four stages of data release starting in July 2012 and running until October 2013.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This was increased to five stages in October 2013.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A detailed commentary accompanies each release along with relevant reference materials.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally there will be graphic visualisations providing further clarification and comparison between different data sets and comparison over time using data from earlier censuses.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] There will also be more specialist reports and products.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Certain data bases will also be produced in the Welsh language.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick univariate (single parameter) statistics based on output levels, with release based on geography.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] (e.g. local authority, wards and parish/ community) tabulated by population count and percentages and accessible by post code.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key Statistics for local authorities in England and Wales comprising data which adds detail to the population estimates published in July 2012.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It includes population information on international migration, age, ethnicity, national identity, health, housing and religion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Wales, there is data on the Welsh language and population data on unitary authorities.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for Output Areas (OAs) and for wards.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Background information covering families, general health and disability, unpaid care, language, occupation and industry, qualifications and economic activity.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics for postcode sectors, health areas and Welsh Government devolved constituencies, and the key statistics for national parks in England and Wales, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for non-UK short-term residents in England and Wales and quick statistics for England and Wales on national identity, passports held and country of birth, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed cross tabulation of data topics: Migration; ethnicity, identity, language and religion; health; and Welsh tables.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed Characteristics tables for the themes of demography and families at local authority, MSOA and ward level.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] English language proficiency for regions, local authorities, 2011 Census Merged Wards and MSOAs in England and Wales.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first Local Characteristics tables for the topics of ethnicity, identity, language and religion for Output Areas, unitary and local authorities and regions.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics tables for the topics of health and unpaid care for Output Areas.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Follow up to Release 3.2b on 12 July 2013.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristic Tables for the topic of migration for Output Areas.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics on travel to work and car and van availability for Output Areas.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the six main releases phases further supplementary, smaller scale and specialist releases including; Small population groups, Microdata (teaching files, safeguarded files and secure files), Origin-destination data, and Alternate population bases.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Northern Ireland were set out by the NISRA.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release phases are closely synchronised with those of the ONS for England and Wales with some marginal variations to allow for local administrative arrangements.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex for Local Government Districts, etc.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Household number and size by geographic units.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key statistics for NI and Local Government Districts etc.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Quick statistics for all geographies and population and household estimates for lower geographies.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI-wide and all local authority and other geographies (including religion, identity and health).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI (including ethnicity, country of birth and language).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Remaining detailed characteristics for NI including labour market and housing.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] All outstanding detailed characteristics for the remaining geographic areas.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate local characteristic tables and detailed themes around: economic activity; country of birth; occupation; and unpaid care.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Scotland were set out by the GROS Release phase dates are partly in sync with those of the other UK constituent country statistical authorities, however the first release was scheduled for six months after the first releases by the other authorities.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Consequently, release of UK-wide data has been scheduled so as to coincide with release plans for Scotland's Census releases.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates, based on resident households, communal establishments and age bands.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Estimates of the usually resident population of Scotland rounded to the nearest thousand, broken down by age and sex.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] An estimate of the total population in each council area, rounded to nearest thousand.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates by five-year age bands and sex for Scotland and each council area.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population and household changes since 2001 census.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population dependency ratios for Scotland and each council area.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] First release of unrounded population estimates and household communal establishment numbers, by single year of age and sex.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] (First published as rounded data in December 2012 and March 2013).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics; Census Profiles; headcounts and geography products.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Comprising; Estimates by postcode and geography products.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This release will represent the start of the dissemination of detailed census statistics for small areas.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for marriage and civil partnership, ethnicity, religion, language proficiency, country of birth and national identity, heath (excluding long-term health), age, arrival in UK, population and households, housing and accommodation, car and van ownership.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: Scotland, Council Areas and Health Boards.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Education and Labour Market.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All output areas and Data Zones.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Also the key and quick statistics for the remaining geographies of the topics covered in Release 2a.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Living Arrangements and Travel to Work Methods.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All levels of census geographies.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate statistics, comprising a combination of; age, sex, resident type, ethnic group, economic activity, general health and provision of unpaid care, country of birth, and occupation.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for Qualifications, Employment and Economic Activity, Travel for Work and Study.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables including; Travel to Work, Household, Qualifications and Long-term Health, Social Status and Economic Activity.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The United Kingdom Statistics Authority is responsible for coordinating the release of census data by the devolved statistics authorities.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It publishes UK-wide census data results via the Office for National Statistics (ONS) site.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The UK Data Service provides a central point of reference for all country-specific census data releases via its Learning Hub site.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Primary responsibility for country-specific 2011 census data rests with the statistical authorities for each of the UK's constituent countries.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each authority has at least one dedicated central source from which data can be downloaded or ordered.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] For England and Wales the ONS provides the access to primary data via its 2011 census siteArchived 29 January 2016 at the UK Government Web Archive.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, data organised by local authority or post code is available on the Neighbourhood Statistics Archived 20 October 2010 at the Wayback Machine site, and nomis, a source of detailed census results which can be assembled into bespoke data sets.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Scotland the General Registrar Office for Scotland (GROS) part of National Records of Scotland (NRS) to maintain access via its Scotlands Census site, and for Northern Ireland the Statistics and Research Authority (NISRA) uses the Northern Ireland Neighbourhood Information Service (NINIS).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The format of all the pre-defined statistical tables is standardised as far as practical across the publishing authorities.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Since the 2001 UK census the naming conventions for the tables have been revised following research into the approaches adopted by other census publishing bodies around the world.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The statistical authorities are also making available bulk data in Comma-separated values (CSV) file format which can be downloaded from online data warehouse facilities.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the standard releases and online bulk access the statistical authorities provide a commissioned data service whereby other data configurations can be purchased, under license, by customers and will subsequently be made freely available to other users.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The title had its origin in the monasteries of Egypt and Syria, spread through the eastern Mediterranean, and soon became accepted generally in all languages as the designation of the head of a monastery.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The word is derived from the Aramaic **av** meaning "father" or **abba**, meaning "my father" (it still has this meaning in contemporary Arabic: أب, Hebrew: אבא and Aramaic: ܐܒܐ) In the Septuagint, it was written as "abbas".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] At first it was employed as a respectful title for any monk, but it was soon restricted by canon law to certain priestly superiors.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] At times it was applied to various priests, e.g. at the court of the Frankish monarchy the **Abbas palatinus** ("of the palace"') and **Abbas castrensis** ("of the camp") were chaplains to the Merovingian and Carolingian sovereigns' court and army respectively.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The title of abbot came into fairly general use in western monastic orders whose members include priests.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The English version for a female monastic head is abbess.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In Egypt, the first home of monasticism, the jurisdiction of the abbot, or archimandrite, was but loosely defined.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Sometimes he ruled over only one community, sometimes over several, each of which had its own abbot as well.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Saint John Cassian speaks of an abbot of the Thebaid who had 500 monks under him.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] By the Rule of St Benedict, which, until the Cluniac reforms, was the norm in the West, the abbot has jurisdiction over only one community.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The rule, as was inevitable, was subject to frequent violations; but it was not until the foundation of the Cluniac Order that the idea of a supreme abbot, exercising jurisdiction over all the houses of an order, was definitely recognised.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Monks, as a rule, were laymen, nor at the outset was the abbot any exception.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] For the reception of the sacraments, and for other religious offices, the abbot and his monks were commanded to attend the nearest church.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] This rule proved inconvenient when a monastery was situated in a desert or at a distance from a city, and necessity compelled the ordination of some monks.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] This innovation was not introduced without a struggle, ecclesiastical dignity being regarded as inconsistent with the higher spiritual life, but, before the close of the 5th century, at least in the East, abbots seem almost universally to have become deacons, if not priests.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The change spread more slowly in the West, where the office of abbot was commonly filled by laymen till the end of the 7th century.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The ecclesiastical leadership exercised by abbots despite their frequent lay status is proved by their attendance and votes at ecclesiastical councils.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Thus at the first Council of Constantinople, AD 448, 23 archimandrites or abbots sign, with 30 bishops.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The second Council of Nicaea, AD 787, recognized the right of abbots to ordain their monks to the inferior orders below the diaconate, a power usually reserved to bishops.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Abbots used to be subject to episcopal jurisdiction, and continued generally so, in fact, in the West till the 11th century.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The Code of Justinian (lib. i. tit. iii. de Ep. leg. xl.) expressly subordinates the abbot to episcopal oversight.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] These exceptions, introduced with a good object, had grown into a widespread evil by the 12th century, virtually creating an *imperium in imperio,* and depriving the bishop of all authority over the chief centres of influence in his diocese.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In the 12th century, the abbots of Fulda claimed precedence of the archbishop of Cologne.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Abbots more and more assumed almost episcopal state, and in defiance of the prohibition of early councils and the protests of St Bernard and others, adopted the episcopal insignia of mitre, ring, gloves and sandals.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] It has been maintained that the right to wear mitres was sometimes granted by the popes to abbots before the 11th century, but the documents on which this claim is based are not genuine (J.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The first undoubted instance is the bull by which Alexander II in 1063 granted the use of the mitre to Egelsinus, abbot of the monastery of St Augustine at Canterbury.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Of these the precedence was yielded to the abbot of Glastonbury, until in AD 1154 Adrian IV (Nicholas Breakspear) granted it to the abbot of St Alban's, in which monastery he had been brought up.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Next after the abbot of St Alban's ranked the abbot of Westminster and then Ramsey.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Elsewhere, the mitred abbots that sat in the Estates of Scotland were of Arbroath, Cambuskenneth, Coupar Angus, Dunfermline, Holyrood, Iona, Kelso, Kilwinning, Kinloss, Lindores, Paisley, Melrose, Scone, St Andrews Priory and Sweetheart.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The adoption of certain episcopal insignia (pontificalia) by abbots was followed by an encroachment on episcopal functions, which had to be specially but ineffectually guarded against by the Lateran council, AD 1123.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Of course, they always and everywhere had the power of admitting their own monks and vesting them with the religious habit.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The power of the abbot was paternal but absolute, limited, however, by the canon law.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] One of the main goals of monasticism was the purgation of self and selfishness, and obedience was seen as a path to that perfection.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] It was sacred duty to execute the abbot's orders, and even to act without his orders was sometimes considered a transgression.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] When a vacancy occurred, the bishop of the diocese chose the abbot out of the monks of the monastery, but the right of election was transferred by jurisdiction to the monks themselves, reserving to the bishop the confirmation of the election and the benediction of the new abbot.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In abbeys exempt from the archbishop's diocesan jurisdiction, the confirmation and benediction had to be conferred by the pope in person, the house being taxed with the expenses of the new abbot's journey to Rome.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In some exceptional cases an abbot was allowed to name his own successor.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Cassian speaks of an abbot in Egypt doing this; and in later times we have another example in the case of St Bruno.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Popes and sovereigns gradually encroached on the rights of the monks, until in Italy the pope had usurped the nomination of all abbots, and the king in France, with the exception of Cluny, Premontré and other houses, chiefs of their order.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The election was for life, unless the abbot was canonically deprived by the chiefs of his order, or when he was directly subject to them, by the pope or the bishop, and also in England it was for a term of 8–12 years.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The ceremony of the formal admission of a Benedictine abbot in medieval times is thus prescribed by the consuetudinary of Abingdon.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The newly elected abbot was to put off his shoes at the door of the church, and proceed barefoot to meet the members of the house advancing in a procession.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] After proceeding up the nave, he was to kneel and pray at the topmost step of the entrance of the choir, into which he was to be introduced by the bishop or his commissary, and placed in his stall.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The monks, then kneeling, gave him the kiss of peace on the hand, and rising, on the mouth, the abbot holding his staff of office.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] He then put on his shoes in the vestry, and a chapter was held, and the bishop or his delegate preached a suitable sermon.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Before the late modern era, the abbot was treated with the utmost reverence by the brethren of his house.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] When he appeared either in church or chapter all present rose and bowed.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] His letters were received kneeling, as were those of the pope and the king.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] No monk might sit in his presence, or leave it, without his permission, reflecting the hierarchical etiquette of families and society.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The highest place was assigned to him, both in church and at table.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In the East he was commanded to eat with the other monks.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In the West, the Rule of St Benedict appointed him a separate table, at which he might entertain guests and strangers.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Because this permission opened the door to luxurious living, Synods of Aachen decreed that the abbot should dine in the refectory, and be content with the ordinary fare of the monks, unless he had to entertain a guest.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] These ordinances proved, however, generally ineffective to secure strictness of diet, and contemporaneous literature abounds with satirical remarks and complaints concerning the inordinate extravagance of the tables of the abbots.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] When the abbot condescended to dine in the refectory, his chaplains waited upon him with the dishes, a servant, if necessary, assisting them.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] When abbots dined in their own private hall, the Rule of St Benedict charged them to invite their monks to their table, provided there was room, on which occasions the guests were to abstain from quarrels, slanderous talk and idle gossiping.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The ordinary attire of the abbot was according to rule to be the same as that of the monks.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] But by the 10th century the rule was commonly set aside, and we find frequent complaints of abbots dressing in silk, and adopting sumptuous attire.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Some even laid aside the monastic habit altogether, and assumed a secular dress.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] With the increase of wealth and power, abbots had lost much of their special religious character, and become great lords, chiefly distinguished from lay lords by celibacy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Thus we hear of abbots going out to hunt, with their men carrying bows and arrows; keeping horses, dogs and huntsmen; and special mention is made of an abbot of Leicester, c.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] 1360, who was the most skilled of all the nobility in hare hunting.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In magnificence of equipage and retinue the abbots vied with the first nobles of the realm.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] They rode on mules with gilded bridles, rich saddles and housings, carrying hawks on their wrist, followed by an immense train of attendants.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The bells of the churches were rung as they passed.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] They associated on equal terms with laymen of the highest distinction, and shared all their pleasures and pursuits.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] This rank and power was, however, often used most beneficially.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] His table, attendance and officers were an honour to the nation.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] He would entertain as many as 500 persons of rank at one time, besides relieving the poor of the vicinity twice a week.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] He had his country houses and fisheries, and when he travelled to attend parliament his retinue amounted to upwards of 100 persons.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The abbots of Cluny and Vendôme were, by virtue of their office, cardinals of the Roman church.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Thus the chief magistrate of the republic at Genoa was called **Abbas Populi**.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] **defensores**, **abbacomites**, **abbates laici**, **abbates milites**, **abbates saeculares** or **irreligiosi**, **abbatiarii**, or sometimes simply **abbates**) were the outcome of the growth of the feudal system from the 8th century onwards.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] During the Carolingian epoch, the custom grew up of granting these as regular heritable fiefs or benefices, and by the 10th century, before the great Cluniac reform, the system was firmly established.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Even the abbey of St Denis was held in commendam by Hugh Capet.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The example of the kings was followed by the feudal nobles, sometimes by making a temporary concession permanent, sometimes without any form of commendation whatever.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In England the abuse was rife in the 8th century, as may be gathered from the acts of the council of Cloveshoe.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] These lay abbacies were not merely a question of overlordship, but implied the concentration in lay hands of all the rights, immunities and jurisdiction of the foundations, i.e. the more or less complete secularization of spiritual institutions.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The lay abbot took his recognized rank in the feudal hierarchy, and was free to dispose of his fief as in the case of any other.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The enfeoffment of abbeys differed in form and degree.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Sometimes the monks were directly subject to the lay abbot; sometimes he appointed a substitute to perform the spiritual functions, known usually as dean (*decanus*), but also as abbot (**abbas legitimus**, **monasticus**, **regularis**).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] When the great reform of the 11th century had put an end to the direct jurisdiction of the lay abbots, the honorary title of abbot continued to be held by certain of the great feudal families, as late as the 13th century and later, with the head of the community retaining the title of dean.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The connection of the lesser lay abbots with the abbeys, especially in the south of France, lasted longer; and certain feudal families retained the title of *abbés chevaliers* (Latin: *abbates milites*) for centuries, together with certain rights over the abbey lands or revenues.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] John, patriarch of Antioch at the beginning of the 12th century, informs us that in his time most monasteries had been handed over to laymen, **beneficiarii**, for life, or for part of their lives, by the emperors.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In conventual cathedrals, where the bishop occupied the place of the abbot, the functions usually devolving on the superior of the monastery were performed by a prior.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In the Roman Catholic Church and Evangelical-Lutheran Churches, abbots continue to be elected by the monks of an abbey to lead them as their religious superior in those orders and monasteries that make use of the term (some orders of monks, as the Carthusians for instance, have only priors).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Prior to this, the monastery would be a mere priory, headed by a prior who acts as superior but without the same degree of legal authority that an abbot has.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The abbot is chosen by the monks from among the fully professed monks.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Once chosen, he must request blessing: the blessing of an abbot is celebrated by the bishop in whose diocese the monastery is or, with his permission, another abbot or bishop.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The ceremony of such a blessing is similar in some aspects to the consecration of a bishop, with the new abbot being presented with the mitre, the ring, and the crosier as symbols of office and receiving the laying on of hands and blessing from the celebrant.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Though the ceremony installs the new abbot into a position of legal authority, it does not confer further sacramental authority- it is not a further degree of Holy Orders (although some abbots have been ordained to the episcopacy).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The abbey is a species of "exempt religious" in that it is, for the most part, answerable to the pope, or to the abbot primate, rather than to the local bishop.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The abbot wears the same habit as his fellow monks, though by tradition he adds to it a pectoral cross.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Territorial abbots follow all of the above, but in addition must receive a mandate of authority from the pope over the territory around the monastery for which they are responsible.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In some monastic families, there is a hierarchy of precedence or authority among abbots.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In some cases, this is the result of an abbey being considered the "mother" of several "daughter" abbeys founded as dependent priories of the "mother".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In other cases, abbeys have affiliated in networks known as "congregations".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Some monastic families recognize one abbey as the motherhouse of the entire order.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] *abate*), as commonly used in the Catholic Church on the European continent, is the equivalent of the English "Father" (parallel etymology), being loosely applied to all who have received the tonsure.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] This use of the title is said to have originated in the right conceded to the king of France, by the concordat between Pope Leo X and Francis I (1516), to appoint commendatory abbots (**abbés commendataires**) to most of the abbeys in France.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The expectation of obtaining these sinecures drew young men towards the church in considerable numbers, and the class of abbés so formed – **abbés de cour** they were sometimes called, and sometimes (ironically) **abbés de sainte espérance** ("abbés of holy hope; or in a jeu de mots, "of St.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Hope") – came to hold a recognized position.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The connection many of them had with the church was of the slenderest kind, consisting mainly in adopting the title of abbé, after a remarkably moderate course of theological study, practising celibacy and wearing distinctive dress, a short dark-violet coat with narrow collar.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Being men of presumed learning and undoubted leisure, many of the class found admission to the houses of the French nobility as tutors or advisers.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The class did not survive the Revolution; but the courtesy title of abbé, having long lost all connection in people's minds with any special ecclesiastical function, remained as a convenient general term applicable to any clergyman.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In the Eastern Orthodox and Eastern Catholic Churches, the abbot is referred to as the *hegumen*.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The Superior of a monastery of nuns is called the *Hēguménē*.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The title of *archimandrite* (literally the head of the enclosure) used to mean something similar.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In the East, the principle set forth in the *Corpus Juris Civilis* still applies, whereby most abbots are immediately subject to the local bishop.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Those monasteries which enjoy the status of being *stauropegic* will be subject only to a primate or his Synod of Bishops and not the local bishop.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In the Eastern Orthodox Church, only monastics are permitted to be elevated to the rank of archimandrite.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Married priests are elevated to the parallel rank of Archpriest or Protopresbyter.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Normally there are no celibate priests who are not monastics in the Orthodox Church, with the exception of married priests who have been widowed.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Since the time of Catherine II the ranks of Abbot and Archimandrite have been given as honorary titles in the Russian Church, and may be given to any monastic, even if he does not in fact serve as the superior of a monastery.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In Greek practice the title or function of Abbot corresponds to a person who serves as the head of a monastery, although the title of the Archimandrite may be given to any celibate priest who could serve as the head of a monastery.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In the German Evangelical Church, the German title of *Abt* (abbot) is sometimes bestowed, like the French *abbé*, as an honorary distinction, and additionally designates the heads of monasteries, with a number of these that accepted the Evangelical-Lutheran faith at the time of the Reformation.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Of these the most noteworthy is Loccum Abbey in Hanover, founded as a Cistercian house in 1163 by Count Wilbrand of Hallermund, and Lutheranised in 1593.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The abbot of Loccum, who still carries a pastoral staff, takes precedence over all the clergy of Hanover, and was *ex officio* a member of the consistory of the kingdom.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The governing body of the abbey consists of the abbot, prior and the "convent", or community, of *Stiftsherren* (canons).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] With respect to Anglicanism, in the Church of England, the Bishop of Norwich, by royal decree given by Henry VIII, also holds the honorary title of "Abbot of St.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Benet." This title hails back to England's separation from the See of Rome, when King Henry, as supreme head of the newly independent church, took over all of the monasteries, mainly for their possessions, except for St.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Benet, which he spared because the abbot and his monks possessed no wealth, and lived like simple beggars, deposing the incumbent Bishop of Norwich and seating the abbot in his place, thus the dual title still held to this day.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Additionally, at the enthronement of the Archbishop of Canterbury, there is a threefold enthronement, once in the throne the chancel as the diocesan bishop of Canterbury, once in the Chair of St.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Augustine as the Primate of All England, and then once in the chapter-house as Titular Abbot of Canterbury.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] There are several Benedictine abbeys throughout the Anglican Communion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] "The Abbot" is one of the archetypes traditionally illustrated in scenes of *Danse Macabre*.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] The lives of numerous abbots make up a significant contribution to Christian hagiography, one of the most well-known being the *Life of St.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] During the years 1106–1107 AD, Daniel, a Russian Orthodox abbot, made a pilgrimage to the Holy Land and recorded his experiences.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] His diary was much-read throughout Russia, and at least seventy-five manuscript copies survive.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] Saint Joseph, Abbot of Volokolamsk, Russia (1439–1515), wrote a number of influential works against heresy, and about monastic and liturgical discipline, and Christian philanthropy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] In the *Tales of Redwall* series, the creatures of Redwall are led by an abbot or abbess.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] These "abbots" are appointed by the brothers and sisters of Redwall to serve as a superior and provide paternal care, much like real abbots.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abbot] "The Abbot" was a nickname of RZA from the Wu-Tang Clan.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] The ***Aberdeen Breviary*** (Latin: ***Breviarium Aberdonense***) is a 16th-century Scottish Catholic breviary.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] It was the first full-length book to be printed in Edinburgh, and in Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] The creation of the Aberdeen Breviary can be seen as one of the features of the growing Scottish nationalism and identity of the early sixteenth century.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] In 1507, King James IV, realizing that the existing Sarum Breviary, or Rite, was English in origin, desired the printing of a Scottish version.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] Since Scotland had no printing press at that time, booksellers Walter Chepman and Androw Myllar of Edinburgh were commissioned to “bring home a printing press” primarily for that purpose.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] To create the breviary itself, James sought out William Elphinstone, Bishop of Aberdeen, who had received the king's permission to establish the University of Aberdeen twelve years before.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] To help him with the undertaking, Elphinstone, in turn, tapped the man who had helped him found the university, Scottish philosopher and historian Hector Boece.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] The two began their work in 1509, and the first copy, produced as a small octavo, came off the press in 1510.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] Like the Sarum Rite, which had been in use since the twelfth century, the Aberdeen Breviary contained brief lives, or biographies, of the saints as well as the liturgy and canonical hours which were to conform to Roman practice and serve as the standard of Christian worship throughout the country.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] The saints’ lives, or biographies, in the breviary were all written by either Elphinstone or Boece.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] Boece once noted that Elphinstone collected legends of saints from every diocese in Scotland, including both national heroes and local saints.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] He also noted that Elphinstone devoted time to the study of ancient Scottish histories, especially in the Western Isles, where “tombs of the ancient kings” lie.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] In addition, some material, such as *Lessons for St Cuthbert,* came from the writings of Bede.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] Some of the collected materials were included verbatim in the breviary, and some were re-written.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] However, unlike the Sarum Rite, the Aberdeen work also contained lives of the nation's saints—Scottish saints such as Kentigern, Machar, and Margaret of Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] Indeed, historian Jane Geddes has gone so far as to call the Aberdeen Breviary a work of “religious patriotism,” pointing out Scotland's sixteenth-century efforts to establish its own identity.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] Along with focusing on Scottish saints, Elphinstone sometimes “Scotticized” Irish and continental saints, one of the most interesting being the office of an Irish missionary in France named Fiacre.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] Historian Steve Boardman speculates Fiacre appealed to the Scots because of their traditional military alliance with France and long history of wars against the English Crown.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] Furthermore, the Irish-born French saint is associated with the death of England's invading King Henry V.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] After the Battle of Agincourt, Henry had allowed his army to pillage Fiacre's monastery and Christian pilgrimage shrine in the town bearing his name, but Fiacre supernaturally prevented the English soldiers from carrying their loot beyond the boundaries of his monastery.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] Henry V died of haemorrhoids on 30 August, St Fiacre's feast day.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] Boardman points out, however, that there are a few cases in which Elphinstone and Boece included saints associated with Scotland, but introduced as otherwise.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] One example is St Constantine the Great, for whom there were dedicated places of worship in Scotland—at Kilchousland in Kintyre and at Govan—and whom Glasgow even claimed as a native son.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] The breviary, which was composed in Latin, includes at the back a small, 16-page book entitled *Compassio Beate Marie*, which has readings about the relics of St Andrew, Scotland's patron saint.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] In addition, at the end of each volume were the *Propria Sanctorum*, containing prayers and readings to be used only on the feast day of the particular saint.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] Hymns, responsories, and antiphons were composed for most of the saints in various metres and styles.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] There are poems as well, although, except for the poem for the office of St Fiacre, they are not high in quality.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] All these were to be used as acts of worship.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] A facsimile of one copy was published in two parts (*Pars estiva* and *Pars hyemalis*) in 1854 & 1855, edited by William Blew; this facsimile was issued to members of the Bannatyne, Maitland and Spalding Clubs.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-breviary] The copy held by the University of Edinburgh has been entirely digitised, and is available for viewing online.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] When done legally in industrialized societies, induced abortion is one of the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Modern methods use medication or surgery for abortions.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The drug mifepristone (aka RU-486) in combination with prostaglandin appears to be as safe and effective as surgery during the first and second trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Self-managed medication abortion is highly effective and safe throughout the first trimester.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The most common surgical technique involves dilating the cervix and using a suction device.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Birth control, such as contraceptive pills or intrauterine devices, can be used immediately following an abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] When performed legally and safely on a woman who desires it, an induced abortion does not increase the risk of long-term mental or physical problems.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In contrast, unsafe abortions performed by unskilled individuals, with hazardous equipment, or in unsanitary facilities cause between 22,000 and 44,000 deaths and 6.9 million hospital admissions each year — responsible for between 5% and 13% of maternal deaths, especially in low-income countries.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization states that "access to legal, safe and comprehensive abortion care, including post-abortion care, is essential for the attainment of the highest possible level of sexual and reproductive health".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Public health data show that making safe abortion legal and accessible reduces maternal deaths.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Around 73 million abortions are performed each year in the world, with about 45% done unsafely.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Abortion rates changed little between 2003 and 2008, before which they decreased for at least two decades as access to family planning and birth control increased.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] As of 2018, 37% of the world's women had access to legal abortions without limits as to reason.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Countries that permit abortions have different limits on how late in pregnancy abortion is allowed.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Abortion rates are similar between countries that restrict abortion and countries that broadly allow it, though this is partly because countries which restrict abortion tend to have higher unintended pregnancy rates.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Since 1973, there has been a global trend towards greater legal access to abortion, but there remains debate with regard to moral, religious, ethical, and legal issues.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Those who oppose abortion often argue that an embryo or fetus is a person with a right to life, and thus equate abortion with murder.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Those who support abortion's legality often argue that it is a woman's reproductive right.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Others favor legal and accessible abortion as a public health measure.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Abortion laws and views of the procedure are different around the world.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In some countries abortion is legal and women have the right to make the choice about abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In some areas, abortion is legal only in specific cases such as rape, incest, fetal defects, poverty, and risk to a woman's health.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Historically, abortions have been attempted using herbal medicines, sharp tools, forceful massage, or other traditional methods.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] An induced abortion is a medical procedure to end a pregnancy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In present-day English, the term *abortion*, when used without further qualification, generally refers to induced abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] A pregnancy can be intentionally aborted in several ways.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The abortion method depends upon the gestational age of the embryo or fetus, which gains mass as the pregnancy progresses.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Abortion laws, regional availability, and the personal preference of the woman and her doctor may inform the woman's choice of a specific abortion procedure.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Abortions can be characterized as either therapeutic or elective.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] When an abortion is performed for medical reasons, the procedure is referred to as a therapeutic abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] An abortion is referred to as elective or voluntary when it is performed at the request of the woman for non-medical reasons.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Confusion sometimes arises over the term *elective* because "elective surgery" generally refers to all scheduled surgery, whether medically necessary or not.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] About one in five pregnancies worldwide ends with an induced abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Most abortions result from unintended pregnancies.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In the United Kingdom, 1 to 2% of abortions are done because of genetic problems in the fetus.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Miscarriage, also known as spontaneous abortion, is the unintentional expulsion of an embryo or fetus before the 24th week of gestation.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] A pregnancy that ends before 37 weeks of gestation resulting in a live-born infant is a "premature birth" or a "preterm birth".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] When a fetus dies in utero after viability, or during delivery, it is usually termed "stillborn".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Premature births and stillbirths are generally not considered to be miscarriages, although usage of these terms can sometimes overlap.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Studies of pregnant women in the US and China have shown that between 40% and 60% of embryos do not progress to birth.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The vast majority of miscarriages occur before the woman is aware that she is pregnant, and many pregnancies spontaneously abort before medical practitioners can detect an embryo.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Between 15% and 30% of known pregnancies end in clinically apparent miscarriage, depending upon the age and health of the pregnant woman.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] 80% of these spontaneous abortions happen in the first trimester.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The most common cause of spontaneous abortion during the first trimester is chromosomal abnormalities of the embryo or fetus, accounting for at least 50% of sampled early pregnancy losses.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Other causes include vascular disease (such as lupus), diabetes, other hormonal problems, infection, and abnormalities of the uterus.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Advancing maternal age and a woman's history of previous spontaneous abortions are the two leading factors associated with a greater risk of spontaneous abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] A spontaneous abortion can also be caused by accidental trauma; intentional trauma or stress to cause miscarriage is considered induced abortion or feticide.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] may determine which abortion methods are practiced.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Medical abortions are those induced by abortifacient pharmaceuticals.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Medical abortion became an alternative method of abortion with the availability of prostaglandin analogs in the 1970s and the antiprogestogen mifepristone (also known as RU-486) in the 1980s.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimens work faster and are more effective at later gestational ages than methotrexate–misoprostol combination regimens, and combination regimens are more effective than misoprostol alone, particularly in the second trimester.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Medical abortion regimens involving mifepristone followed by misoprostol in the cheek between 24 and 48 hours later are effective when performed before 70 days' gestation.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In very early abortions, up to 7 weeks gestation, medical abortion using a mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimen is considered to be more effective than surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration), especially when clinical practice does not include detailed inspection of aspirated tissue.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Early medical abortion regimens using mifepristone, followed 24–48 hours later by buccal or vaginal misoprostol are 98% effective up to 9 weeks gestational age; from 9 to 10 weeks efficacy decreases modestly to 94%.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] If medical abortion fails, surgical abortion must be used to complete the procedure.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Early medical abortions account for the majority of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in Britain, France, Switzerland, United States, and the Nordic countries.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] A 2020 Cochrane Systematic Review concluded that providing women with medications to take home to complete the second stage of the procedure for an early medical abortion results in an effective abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Further research is required to determine if self-administered medical abortion is as safe as provider-administered medical abortion, where a health care professional is present to help manage the medical abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Safely permitting women to self-administer abortion medication has the potential to improve access to abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The review also noted a research gap concerning methods to support women who take medication at home for a self-administered abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Up to 15 weeks' gestation, suction-aspiration or vacuum aspiration are the most common surgical methods of induced abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] *Manual vacuum aspiration* (MVA) consists of removing the fetus or embryo, placenta, and membranes by suction using a manual syringe, while *electric vacuum aspiration* (EVA) uses an electric pump.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Both techniques can be used very early in pregnancy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] MVA can be used up to 14 weeks but is more often used earlier in the U.S.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] MVA, also known as "mini-suction" and "menstrual extraction", or EVA can be used in very early pregnancy when cervical dilation may not be required.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Dilation and curettage (D&C) refers to opening the cervix (dilation) and removing tissue (curettage) via suction or sharp instruments.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] D&C is a standard gynecological procedure performed for a variety of reasons, including examination of the uterine lining for possible malignancy, investigation of abnormal bleeding, and abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization recommends *sharp curettage* only when suction aspiration is unavailable.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Dilation and evacuation (D&E), used after 12 to 16 weeks, consists of opening the cervix and removing pregnancy tissue and fetal parts with suction and forceps.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] D&E is performed vaginally and does not require an incision.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Intact dilation and extraction (D&X) refers to a variant of D&E sometimes used after 18 to 20 weeks when removal of an intact fetus improves surgical safety or for other reasons.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Abortion may also be performed surgically by hysterotomy or gravid hysterectomy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy abortion is a procedure similar to a caesarean section and is performed under general anesthesia.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] It requires a smaller incision than a caesarean section and can be used during later stages of pregnancy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Gravid hysterectomy refers to removal of the whole uterus while still containing the pregnancy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy and hysterectomy are associated with much higher rates of maternal morbidity and mortality than D&E or induction abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] First trimester procedures can generally be performed using local anesthesia, while second trimester methods may require deep sedation or general anesthesia.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In places lacking the necessary medical skill for dilation and extraction, or when preferred by practitioners, an abortion can be induced by first inducing labor and then inducing fetal demise if necessary.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] This is sometimes called "induced miscarriage".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] This procedure may be performed from 13 weeks gestation to the third trimester.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Although it is very uncommon in the United States, more than 80% of induced abortions throughout the second trimester are labor-induced abortions in Sweden and other nearby countries.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Only limited data are available comparing labor-induced abortion with the dilation and extraction method.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Unlike D&E, labor-induced abortions after 18 weeks may be complicated by the occurrence of brief fetal survival, which may be legally characterized as live birth.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] For this reason, labor-induced abortion is legally risky in the United States.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Historically, a number of herbs reputed to possess abortifacient properties have been used in folk medicine.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Such herbs include tansy, pennyroyal, black cohosh, and the now-extinct silphium.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In 1978, one woman in Colorado died and another developed organ damage when they attempted to terminate their pregnancies by taking pennyroyal oil.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Because the indiscriminant use of herbs as abortifacients can cause serious—even lethal—side effects, such as multiple organ failure, such use is not recommended by physicians.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Abortion is sometimes attempted by causing trauma to the abdomen.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The degree of force, if severe, can cause serious internal injuries without necessarily succeeding in inducing miscarriage.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In Southeast Asia, there is an ancient tradition of attempting abortion through forceful abdominal massage.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] One of the bas reliefs decorating the temple of Angkor Wat in Cambodia depicts a demon performing such an abortion upon a woman who had been sent to the underworld.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Reported methods of unsafe, self-induced abortion include misuse of misoprostol and insertion of non-surgical implements such as knitting needles and clothes hangers into the uterus.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] These and other methods to terminate pregnancy may be called "induced miscarriage".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Such methods are rarely used in countries where surgical abortion is legal and available.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The health risks of abortion depend principally on how, and under what conditions, the procedure is performed.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) defines unsafe abortions as a procedure for terminating an unintended pregnancy carried out either by persons lacking the necessary skills or in an environment that does not conform to minimal medical standards, or both.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Legal abortions performed in the developed world are among the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] According to a 2012 study in *Obstetrics & Gynecology*, in the United States the risk of maternal mortality is 14 times lower after induced abortion than after childbirth.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The CDC estimated in 2019 that US pregnancy-related mortality was 17.2 maternal deaths per 100,000 live births, while the US abortion mortality rate was 0.43 maternal deaths per 100,000 procedures.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In the UK, guidelines of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists state that "Women should be advised that abortion is generally safer than continuing a pregnancy to term." Worldwide, on average, abortion is safer than carrying a pregnancy to term.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In the US from 2000 to 2009, abortion had a mortality rate lower than plastic surgery, lower or similar to running a marathon, and about equivalent to traveling 760 miles (1,220 km) in a passenger car.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Outpatient abortion is as safe from 64 to 70 days' gestation as it before 63 days.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] A 2019 study indicated that five years after seeking abortion services, women who gave birth after being denied an abortion reported worse health than women who had either first or second trimester abortions.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] There is little difference in terms of safety and efficacy between medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol and surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration) in early first trimester abortions up to 10 weeks gestation.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Medical abortion using the prostaglandin analog misoprostol alone is less effective and more painful than medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol or surgical abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Vacuum aspiration in the first trimester is the safest method of surgical abortion, and can be performed in a primary care office, abortion clinic, or hospital.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Complications, which are rare, can include uterine perforation, pelvic infection, and retained products of conception requiring a second procedure to evacuate.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Infections account for one-third of abortion-related deaths in the United States.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The rate of complications of vacuum aspiration abortion in the first trimester is similar regardless of whether the procedure is performed in a hospital, surgical center, or office.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Preventive antibiotics (such as doxycycline or metronidazole) are typically given before abortion procedures, as they are believed to substantially reduce the risk of postoperative uterine infection; however, antibiotics are not routinely given with abortion pills.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The rate of failed procedures does not appear to vary significantly depending on whether the abortion is performed by a doctor or a mid-level practitioner.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Complications after second trimester abortion are similar to those after first trimester abortion, and depend somewhat on the method chosen.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The risk of death from abortion approaches roughly half the risk of death from childbirth the farther along a woman is in pregnancy; from one in a million before 9 weeks gestation to nearly one in ten thousand at 21 weeks or more (as measured from the last menstrual period).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] It appears that having had a prior surgical uterine evacuation (whether because of induced abortion or treatment of miscarriage) correlates with a small increase in the risk of preterm birth in future pregnancies.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The studies supporting this did not control for factors not related to abortion or miscarriage, and hence the causes of this correlation have not been determined, although multiple possibilities have been suggested.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Current evidence finds no relationship between most induced abortions and mental health problems other than those expected for any unwanted pregnancy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Some older reviews concluded that abortion was associated with an increased risk of psychological problems; however, later reviews of the medical literature found that previous reviews did not use an appropriate control group.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] When a control group is utilized, receiving abortion is not associated with adverse psychological outcomes.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] However, women seeking abortion who are denied access to abortion have an increase in anxiety after the denial.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Although some studies show negative mental-health outcomes in women who choose abortions after the first trimester because of fetal abnormalities, more rigorous research would be needed to show this conclusively.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Some proposed negative psychological effects of abortion have been referred to by anti-abortion advocates as a separate condition called "post-abortion syndrome", but this is not recognized by medical or psychological professionals in the United States.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] A 2020 long term-study among US women found that about 99% of women felt that they made the right decision five years after they had an abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Relief was the primary emotion with few women feeling sadness or guilt.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Social stigma was a main factor predicting negative emotions and regret years later.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Some purported risks of abortion are promoted primarily by anti-abortion groups, but lack scientific support.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] For example, the question of a link between induced abortion and breast cancer has been investigated extensively.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Major medical and scientific bodies (including the WHO, National Cancer Institute, American Cancer Society, Royal College of OBGYN and American Congress of OBGYN) have concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In the past even illegality has not automatically meant that the abortions were unsafe.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] A 1940s American physician spoke of his pride in having performed 13,844 illegal abortions without any fatalities.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In 1870s New York City, the abortionist/midwife Madame Restell (Anna Trow Lohman) is said to have lost very few women among her more than 100,000 patients—a lower mortality rate than the childbirth mortality rate at the time.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In 1936, obstetrics and gynecology professor Frederick J.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Women seeking an abortion may use unsafe methods, especially when abortion is legally restricted.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] They may attempt self-induced abortion or seek the help of a person without proper medical training or facilities.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] This can lead to severe complications, such as incomplete abortion, sepsis, hemorrhage, and damage to internal organs.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are a major cause of injury and death among women worldwide.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Although data are imprecise, it is estimated that approximately 20 million unsafe abortions are performed annually, with 97% taking place in developing countries.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are believed to result in millions of injuries.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Estimates of deaths vary according to methodology, and have ranged from 37,000 to 70,000 in the past decade; deaths from unsafe abortion account for around 13% of all maternal deaths.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization believes that mortality has fallen since the 1990s.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] To reduce the number of unsafe abortions, public health organizations have generally advocated emphasizing the legalization of abortion, training of medical personnel, and ensuring access to reproductive-health services.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] A major factor in whether abortions are performed safely or not is the legal standing of abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Countries with restrictive abortion laws have higher rates of unsafe abortion and similar overall abortion rates compared to countries where abortion is legal and available.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] For example, the 1996 legalization of abortion in South Africa led to an immediate reduction in abortion-related complications, with abortion-related deaths dropping by more than 90%.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Similar reductions in maternal mortality have been observed after other countries have liberalized their abortion laws, such as Romania and Nepal.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] A 2011 study concluded that in the United States, some state-level anti-abortion laws are correlated with lower rates of abortion in that state.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The analysis, however, did not take into account travel to other states without such laws to obtain an abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In addition, a lack of access to effective contraception contributes to unsafe abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] It has been estimated that the incidence of unsafe abortion could be reduced by up to 75% (from 20 million to 5 million annually) if modern family planning and maternal health services were readily available globally.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Rates of such abortions may be difficult to measure because they can be reported variously as miscarriage, "induced miscarriage", "menstrual regulation", "mini-abortion", and "regulation of a delayed/suspended menstruation".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Forty percent of the world's women are able to access therapeutic and elective abortions within gestational limits, while an additional 35 percent have access to legal abortion if they meet certain physical, mental, or socioeconomic criteria.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] While maternal mortality seldom results from safe abortions, unsafe abortions result in 70,000 deaths and 5 million disabilities per year.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Complications of unsafe abortion account for approximately an eighth of maternal mortalities worldwide, though this varies by region.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Secondary infertility caused by an unsafe abortion affects an estimated 24 million women.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The rate of unsafe abortions has increased from 44% to 49% between 1995 and 2008.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Health education, access to family planning, and improvements in health care during and after abortion have been proposed to address consequences of unsafe abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In many places, where abortion is illegal or carries a heavy social stigma, medical reporting of abortion is not reliable.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] For this reason, estimates of the incidence of abortion must be made without determining certainty related to standard error.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The number of abortions performed worldwide was characterized as stable in the early 2000s, with 41.6 million having been performed in 2003 and 43.8 million having been performed in 2008.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The abortion rate worldwide was 28 per 1000 women per year, though it was 24 per 1000 women per year for developed countries and 29 per 1000 women per year for developing countries.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The same 2012 study indicated that in 2008, the estimated abortion percentage of known pregnancies was at 21% worldwide, with 26% in developed countries and 20% in developing countries.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] On average, the incidence of abortion is similar in countries with restrictive abortion laws and those with more liberal access to abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Restrictive abortion laws are associated with increases in the percentage of abortions performed unsafely.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The rate of legal, induced abortion varies extensively worldwide.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] According to the report of employees of Guttmacher Institute it ranged from 7 per 1000 women per year (Germany and Switzerland) to 30 per 1000 women per year (Estonia) in countries with complete statistics in 2008.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The proportion of pregnancies that ended in induced abortion ranged from about 10% (Israel, the Netherlands and Switzerland) to 30% (Estonia) in the same group, though it might be as high as 36% in Hungary and Romania, whose statistics were deemed incomplete.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] An American study in 2002 concluded that about half of women having abortions were using a form of contraception at the time of becoming pregnant.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Inconsistent use was reported by half of those using condoms and three-quarters of those using the birth control pill; 42% of those using condoms reported failure through slipping or breakage.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Of the other half of women, who were not using contraception at the time of becoming pregnant, the vast majority had used contraception at some point in the past, indicating some level of dissatisfaction with the contraceptive options available to them.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Indeed, 32% of these contraceptive nonusers cited concerns about contraceptive methods as their reason for nonuse, and a more recent study found similar results.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Taken together, these statistics suggest that new contraceptive methods, such as non-hormonal contraceptives or male contraceptives, could reduce unintended pregnancy and abortion rates.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute has found that "most abortions in the United States are obtained by minority women" because minority women "have much higher rates of unintended pregnancy".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] in England and Wales during 2019 (left).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Abortion in the United States by gestational age, 2016 (right).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Abortion rates vary depending on the stage of pregnancy and the method practiced.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] 91% of these were classified as having been done by "curettage" (suction-aspiration, dilation and curettage, dilation and evacuation), 8% by "medical" means (mifepristone), >1% by "intrauterine instillation" (saline or prostaglandin), and 1% by "other" (including hysterotomy and hysterectomy).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] According to the CDC, due to data collection difficulties the data must be viewed as tentative and some fetal deaths reported beyond 20 weeks may be natural deaths erroneously classified as abortions if the removal of the dead fetus is accomplished by the same procedure as an induced abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute estimated there were 2,200 intact dilation and extraction procedures in the US during 2000; this accounts for <0.2% of the total number of abortions performed that year.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Similarly, in England and Wales in 2006, 89% of terminations occurred at or under 12 weeks, 9% between 13 and 19 weeks, and 2% at or over 20 weeks.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] 64% of those reported were by vacuum aspiration, 6% by D&E, and 30% were medical.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] There are more second trimester abortions in developing countries such as China, India and Vietnam than in developed countries.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] There are both medical and non-medical reasons to have an abortion later in pregnancy (after 20 weeks).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] A study was conducted from 2008 to 2010 at the University of California San Francisco where more than 440 women were asked about why they experienced delays in obtaining abortion care, if there were any.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] This study found that almost half of individuals who obtained an abortion after 20 weeks did not suspect that they were pregnant until later in their pregnancy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Other barriers to abortion care found in the study included lack of information about where to access an abortion, difficulties with transportation, lack of insurance coverage, and inability to pay for the abortion procedure.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Medical reasons for seeking an abortion later in pregnancy include fetal anomalies and health risk to the pregnant person.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] There are prenatal tests that can diagnose Down Syndrome or cystic fibrosis as early as 10 weeks into gestation, but structural fetal anomalies are often detected much later in pregnancy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] A proportion of structural fetal anomalies are lethal, which means that the fetus will almost certainly die before or shortly after birth.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Life-threatening conditions may also develop later in pregnancy, such as early severe preeclampsia, newly diagnosed cancer in need of urgent treatment, and intrauterine infection (chorioamnionitis), which often occurs along with premature rupture of the amniotic sac (PPROM).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] If serious medical conditions such as these arise before the fetus is viable, the person carrying the pregnancy may pursue an abortion to preserve their own health.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The reasons why women have abortions are diverse and vary across the world.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Some of the reasons may include an inability to afford a child, domestic violence, lack of support, feeling they are too young, and the wish to complete education or advance a career.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Additional reasons include not being able or willing to raise a child conceived as a result of rape or incest.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Some abortions are undergone as the result of societal pressures.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] These factors can sometimes result in compulsory abortion or sex-selective abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In cultures where there is a preference for male children, some women have sex selective abortions, which have partially replaced the earlier practice of female infanticide.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Some abortions are performed due to concerns over maternal health.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In 1990s, women cited maternal health as their main motivating factor in about a third of abortions in three of 27 countries analyzed.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In seven additional countries, about 7% of abortions were maternal health related.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In the U.S., the Supreme Court decisions in *Roe v.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Bolton*: "ruled that the state's interest in the life of the fetus became compelling only at the point of viability, defined as the point at which the fetus can survive independently of its mother.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Even after the point of viability, the state cannot favor the life of the fetus over the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Under the right of privacy, physicians must be free to use their "medical judgment for the preservation of the life or health of the mother".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] On the same day that the Court decided Roe, it also decided Doe v.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Bolton, in which the Court defined health very broadly: "The medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The rate of cancer during pregnancy is 0.02–1%, and in many cases, cancer of the mother leads to consideration of abortion to protect the life of the mother, or in response to the potential damage that may occur to the fetus during treatment.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] This is particularly true for cervical cancer, the most common type of which occurs in 1 of every 2,000–13,000 pregnancies, for which initiation of treatment "cannot co-exist with preservation of fetal life (unless neoadjuvant chemotherapy is chosen)".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Very early stage cervical cancers (I and IIa) may be treated by radical hysterectomy and pelvic lymph node dissection, radiation therapy, or both, while later stages are treated by radiotherapy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Chemotherapy may be used simultaneously.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Treatment of breast cancer during pregnancy also involves fetal considerations, because lumpectomy is discouraged in favor of modified radical mastectomy unless late-term pregnancy allows follow-up radiation therapy to be administered after the birth.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Exposure to a single chemotherapy drug is estimated to cause a 7.5–17% risk of teratogenic effects on the fetus, with higher risks for multiple drug treatments.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Treatment with more than 40 Gy of radiation usually causes spontaneous abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Exposure to much lower doses during the first trimester, especially 8 to 15 weeks of development, can cause intellectual disability or microcephaly, and exposure at this or subsequent stages can cause reduced intrauterine growth and birth weight.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Exposures above 0.005–0.025 Gy cause a dose-dependent reduction in IQ.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] It is possible to greatly reduce exposure to radiation with abdominal shielding, depending on how far the area to be irradiated is from the fetus.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The process of birth itself may also put the mother at risk.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Congenital disorders, revealed by prenatal screening, motivate some women to seek abortions.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Health outcomes of preterm births include a significant probability of long-term neurodevelopmental impairment before gestational age of 29 weeks, with a higher probability with decreasing gestational age.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In the United States, public opinion shifted after television personality Sherri Finkbine's was exposed to thalidomide, a teratogen, in her fifth month of pregnancy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Unable to obtain a legal abortion in the United States, Finkbine traveled to Sweden.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] From 1962 to 1965, an outbreak of German measles left 15,000 babies with severe birth defects.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In 1967, the American Medical Association publicly supported liberalization of abortion laws.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] A National Opinion Research Center poll in 1965 showed 73% supported abortion when the mother's life was at risk, 57% when birth defects were present and 59% for pregnancies resulting from rape or incest.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Since ancient times, abortions have been done using a number of methods, including herbal medicines acting as abortifacients, sharp tools through the use of force, or through other traditional medicine methods.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Induced abortion has a long history and can be traced back to civilizations as varied as ancient China (abortifacient knowledge is often attributed to the mythological ruler Shennong), ancient India since its Vedic age, ancient Egypt with its Ebers Papyrus (c.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] 1550 BCE), and the Roman Empire in the time of Juvenal (c.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] One of the earliest known artistic representations of abortion is in a bas relief at Angkor Wat (c.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Found in a series of friezes that represent judgment after death in Hindu and Buddhist culture, it depicts the technique of abdominal abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In *Politics* (350 BCE), Aristotle condemned infanticide as a means of population control.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] He preferred abortion in such cases, with the restriction that it "must be practised on it before it has developed sensation and life; for the line between lawful and unlawful abortion will be marked by the fact of having sensation and being alive".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Abortion has been a fairly common practice, and was not always illegal or controversial until the 19th century.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In Europe and North America, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century; the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Other medical practitioners in addition to some physicians advertised their services, and they were not widely regulated until the 19th century when the practice, sometimes called *restellism*, was banned in both the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Some 19th-century physicians, argued for anti-abortion laws on racist and misogynist as well as moral grounds.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Church groups were also highly influential in anti-abortion movements, and religious groups more so since the 20th century.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Some of the early anti-abortion laws punished only the doctor or abortionist, and while women could be criminally tried for a self-induced abortion, they were rarely prosecuted in general.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Some maintain that in the 19th century early abortions under the hygienic conditions in which midwives usually worked were relatively safe.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Several scholars argue that, despite improved medical procedures, the period from the 1930s until the 1970s saw more zealous enforcement of anti-abortion laws, alongside an increasing control of abortion providers by organized crime.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In 1920, Soviet Russia became the first country to legalize abortion after Lenin insisted that no woman be forced to give birth.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Abortion was then legalized in some form in Iceland (1935), Sweden (1938), Nazi Germany (1935) and Japan (1948) Beginning in the second half of the 20th century, abortion was legalized in a greater number of countries.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In the Catholic Church, opinion was divided on how serious abortion was in comparison with such acts as contraception and oral or anal sex.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The Catholic Church did not begin vigorously opposing abortion until the 19th century.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] As early as ~100 CE, the *Didache* taught that abortion was sinful.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Several historians argue that prior to the 19th century most Catholic authors did not regard termination of pregnancy before quickening or ensoulment as an abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] 1585–1590) was the first Pope to institute a Church policy labeling all abortion as homicide and condemning abortion regardless of the stage of pregnancy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Sixtus V's pronouncement was reversed in 1591 by Pope Gregory XIV.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In the recodification of 1917 Code of Canon Law, *Apostolicae Sedis* was strengthened, in part to remove a possible reading that excluded excommunication of the mother.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Statements made in the *Catechism of the Catholic Church*, the codified summary of the Church's teachings, considers abortion from the moment of conception as homicide and called for the end of legal abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Denominations that support abortion rights with some limits include the United Methodist Church, Episcopal Church, Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and Presbyterian Church USA.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] A 2014 Guttmacher survey of abortion patients in the United States found that many reported a religious affiliation: 24% were Catholic while 30% were Protestant.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] A 1995 survey reported that Catholic women are as likely as the general population to terminate a pregnancy, Protestants are less likely to do so, and evangelical Christians are the least likely to do so.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] A 2019 Pew Research Center study found that most Christian denominations were against overturning *Roe v.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Wade,* which in the United States legalized abortion, at around 70%, except White Evangelicals at 35%.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In Judaism, the fetus is not considered to have a human soul until it is safely outside of the woman, is viable, and has taken its first breath.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] The fetus is considered valuable property of the woman and not a human life while in the womb (Exodus 21:22-23).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] While Judaism encourages people to be fruitful and multiply by having children, abortion is allowed and is deemed necessary when a pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Several religions, including Judaism, which disagree that human life begins at conception, support the legality of abortion on religious freedom grounds.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] In Islam, abortion is traditionally permitted until a point in time when Muslims believe the soul enters the fetus, considered by various theologians to be at conception, 40 days after conception, 120 days after conception, or at quickening.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Abortion is largely heavily restricted or forbidden in areas of high Islamic faith such as the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Hindu views on abortion are diverse and lack a single authoritative position, shaped by principles like ahimsa (non-violence), karma, and reincarnation, which typically regard it as morally wrong for interrupting the soul's cycle.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Scriptures often equate abortion to grave sins, with the fetus considered ensouled from conception or early gestation.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] However, it may be ethically permissible to save the mother's life or in cases of severe fetal abnormalities, prioritizing lesser harm.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p01] Modern opinions differ regionally: In India, a majority view abortion as generally illegal, while in the US, most Hindus support legal access in all or most cases.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Induced abortion has long been the source of considerable debate.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Ethical, moral, philosophical, biological, religious and legal issues surrounding abortion are related to value systems.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Opinions of abortion may be about fetal rights, governmental authority, and women's rights.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] In both public and private debate, arguments presented in favor of or against abortion access focus on either the moral permissibility of an induced abortion, or the justification of laws permitting or restricting abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] The World Medical Association Declaration on Therapeutic Abortion notes, "circumstances bringing the interests of a mother into conflict with the interests of her unborn child create a dilemma and raise the question as to whether or not the pregnancy should be deliberately terminated".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Abortion debates, especially pertaining to abortion laws, are often spearheaded by groups advocating one of these two positions.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Groups who favor greater legal restrictions on abortion, including complete prohibition, most often describe themselves as "pro-life" while groups who are against such legal restrictions describe themselves as "pro-choice".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] The median voters stance on abortion varies by jurisdiction and can result in swing votes.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Current laws pertaining to abortion are diverse.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Religious, moral, and cultural factors continue to influence abortion laws throughout the world.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] The right to life, the right to liberty, the right to security of person, and the right to reproductive health are major issues of human rights that sometimes constitute the basis for the existence or absence of abortion laws.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] In jurisdictions where abortion is legal, certain requirements must often be met before a woman may obtain a legal abortion (an abortion performed without the woman's consent is considered feticide and is generally illegal).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] These requirements usually depend on the age of the fetus, often using a trimester-based system to regulate the window of legality, or as in the U.S., on a doctor's evaluation of the fetus' viability.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Some jurisdictions require a waiting period before the procedure, prescribe the distribution of information on fetal development, or require that parents be contacted if their minor daughter requests an abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Many restrictions are waived in emergency situations.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] China, which has ended their one-child policy, and now has a three-child policy, has at times incorporated mandatory abortions as part of their population control strategy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Other jurisdictions ban abortion almost entirely.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Many, but not all, of these allow legal abortions in a variety of circumstances.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] These circumstances vary based on jurisdiction, but may include whether the pregnancy is a result of rape or incest, the fetus' development is impaired, the woman's physical or mental well-being is endangered, or socioeconomic considerations make childbirth a hardship.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] In countries where abortion is banned entirely, such as Nicaragua, medical authorities have recorded rises in maternal death directly and indirectly due to pregnancy as well as deaths due to doctors' fears of prosecution if they treat other gynecological emergencies.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Some countries, such as Bangladesh, that nominally ban abortion, may also support clinics that perform abortions under the guise of menstrual hygiene.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] This is also a terminology in traditional medicine.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] In places where abortion is illegal or carries heavy social stigma, pregnant women may engage in medical tourism and travel to countries where they can terminate their pregnancies.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Women on Waves has provided medication abortion and education on a ship in international waters off the coast of countries with restrictive abortion laws.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Women without the means to travel can resort to providers of illegal abortions or attempt to perform an abortion by themselves.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Sonography and amniocentesis allow parents to determine sex before childbirth.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] The development of this technology has led to sex-selective abortion, or the termination of a fetus based on its sex.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] The selective termination of a female fetus is most common.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Sex-selective abortion is partially responsible for the noticeable disparities between the birth rates of male and female children in some countries.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] The preference for male children is reported in many areas of Asia, and abortion used to limit female births has been reported in Taiwan, South Korea, India, and China.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] This deviation from the standard birth rates of males and females occurs despite the fact that the country in question may have officially banned sex-selective abortion or even sex-screening.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Many countries have taken legislative steps to reduce the incidence of sex-selective abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] At the International Conference on Population and Development in 1994 over 180 states agreed to eliminate "all forms of discrimination against the girl child and the root causes of son preference", conditions also condemned by a PACE resolution in 2011.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] On the other hand, measures to reduce gender inequality can reduce the prevalence of such abortions without attendant negative consequences.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Abortion providers and facilities have been subjected to violence, including murder, assault, arson, and bombing.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Some scholars consider anti-abortion violence to be within the definition of terrorism, a view shared by some governments.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] In the U.S. and Canada, over 8,000 incidents of violence, trespassing, and death threats have been recorded by providers since 1977, including over 200 bombings/arsons and hundreds of assaults.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Abortion clinics have also been targeted by acid attacks, invasions, and vandalism The majority of abortion opponents have not been involved in violent acts.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Physicians and other abortion clinic staff have been murdered by abortion opponents.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] In the United States, at least four physicians have been murdered in connection with their work at abortion clinics, including David Gunn (1993), John Britton (1994), Barnett Slepian (1998), and George Tiller (2009).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] In Canada, gynecologist Garson Romalis survived murder attempts in both 1994 and 2000.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Besides physicians, killings have targeted other clinic staff, such as John Salvi's 1994 murder of two receptionists in Massachusetts clinic and Peter Knight's 2001 murder of a security guard in a Melbourne clinic.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Notable perpetrators of anti-abortion violence include Eric Rudolph, Scott Roeder, Shelley Shannon, and Paul Hill, the first person to be executed in the United States for murdering an abortion provider.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Some countries have laws to protecting access to abortion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Such laws prevent abortion opponents from interfering with access to legal abortion services.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] For example, the American Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act bars the use of threats or violence to interfere with abortion access.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Abortion access laws may also establish safe access zones around abortion clinics, with limits on protests and enhanced penalties for anti-abortion violence.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Psychological pressure may also be used to limit abortion access.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Some protestors record women entering clinics on camera.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Spontaneous abortion occurs in various animals.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] For example, in sheep it may be caused by stress or physical exertion, such as crowding through doors or being chased by dogs.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] In cows, abortion may be caused by contagious disease, such as brucellosis or *Campylobacter*, but can often be controlled by vaccination.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Eating pine needles can also induce abortions in cows.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Several plants, including broomweed, skunk cabbage, poison hemlock, and tree tobacco, are known to cause fetal deformities and abortion in cattle, and in sheep and goats.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] In horses, a fetus may be aborted or resorbed if it has lethal white syndrome.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Foal embryos that are homozygous for the dominant white gene (WW) are theorized to also be aborted or resorbed before birth.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] In many species of sharks and rays, stress-induced abortions occur frequently upon capture.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Viral infection can cause abortion in dogs.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Cats can experience spontaneous abortion for many reasons, including hormonal imbalance.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] A combined abortion and spaying are performed on pregnant cats, especially in trap–neuter–return programs, to prevent unwanted kittens from being born.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Female rodents may terminate a pregnancy when exposed to the smell of a male not responsible for the pregnancy, known as the Bruce effect.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Abortion may also be induced in animals, in the context of animal husbandry.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] For example, abortion may be induced in mares that have been mated improperly, or that have been purchased by owners who did not realize the mares were pregnant, or that are pregnant with twin foals.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Feticide can occur in horses and zebras due to male harassment of pregnant mares or forced copulation, although the frequency in the wild has been questioned.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/abortion-p02] Male gray langur monkeys may attack females following male takeover, causing miscarriage.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The **Catholic Church in Scotland**, overseen by the Scottish Bishops' Conference, is part of the worldwide Catholic Church headed by the Pope.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Christianity first arrived in Roman Britain and was strengthened by the conversion of the Picts through both the Hiberno-Scottish mission and Iona Abbey.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] After being firmly established in Scotland for nearly a millennium, the Catholic Church was outlawed by the Scottish Reformation Parliament in 1560.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Multiple uprisings in the interim failed to reestablish Catholicism or to legalise its existence.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Even today, the Papal Jurisdiction Act 1560, while no longer enforced, still remains on the books.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Throughout the nearly three centuries of religious persecution and disenfranchisement between 1560-1829, many students for the priesthood went abroad to study while others remained in Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In what is now termed underground education, many attended illegal seminaries.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] An early seminary upon Eilean Bàn in Loch Morar was moved during the Jacobite rising of 1715 and reopened as Scalan seminary in Glenlivet.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] After multiple arson attacks by government troops, Scalan was rebuilt in the 1760s by Bishop John Geddes, who later became Vicar Apostolic of the Lowland District, a close friend of national poet Robert Burns, and a well-known figure in the Edinburgh intelligentsia during the Scottish Enlightenment.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The successful campaign that resulted in Catholic emancipation in 1829 helped Catholics regain both freedom of religion and civil rights.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In 1878, the Catholic hierarchy was formally restored.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] However, there are also significant numbers of Scottish Catholics of Italian, Lithuanian, Ukrainian, and Polish descent, with more recent immigration to Scotland from European Union member states again boosting the numbers.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Owing to immigration (overwhelmingly White European), it is estimated that in 2009, there were about 850,000 Catholics in the country of 5.1 million.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The Gàidhealtachd has been both Catholic and Protestant in modern times.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] A number of Scottish Gaelic-speaking areas, including Barra, Benbecula, South Uist, Eriskay, and Moidart, are predominantly Catholic.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In the 2011 UK Census, 16% of the population of Scotland described themselves as being Roman Catholic, compared with 32% affiliated with the Church of Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Between 1994-2002, Catholic church attendance in Scotland declined 19% to just over 200,000.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] By 2008, the Catholic Bishops' Conference of Scotland estimated that 184,283 attended Mass regularly.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Mass attendance has not recovered to the numbers prior to the COVID-19 pandemic, though there was a dramatic rise between 2022-23.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Christianity may have been introduced to what is now Scotland by soldiers of the Roman Legions stationed in the far north of the province of Britannia.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Like it's faithful, however, Christianity was slowly driven westward with refugees from the Anglo-Saxon invasion of Britain.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] These missionaries tended to found monastic institutions, which expanded to include schools, libraries, and collegiate churches whose priests both evangelized and served large areas.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Partly as a result of these factors, some scholars have identified a distinctive Celtic Church, to which Catholics, Protestants, Miaphysite Orthodox, and Eastern Orthodox, have all claimed in historical debates to be the only legitimate heirs.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] During the 1960s, Frank O'Connor explained that the reason why, on both sides of the Irish Sea, abbots were often more significant than bishops is because a Church governed by an Episcopal polity, "in a tribal society was a contradiction in terms.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The Culdees, an eremitical order from Gaelic Ireland, also spread to Scotland, where their presence continued at least into the 11th-century.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Due to the close ties between the Church in both countries, the erenagh system also spread to Gaelic Scotland, with at least some similar results.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] After the conversion, successful war for political independence from Norway, and increasing Gaelicisation of Scandinavian Scotland and the Isle of Man under Somerled and his heirs, the Roman Rite Diocese of the Isles under bishops appointed by the Holy See became the dominant religion.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] During the reign of King Malcolm III, the Scottish church underwent a series of reforms and transformations.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Through the influence of his Hungarian-born wife, St Margaret of Scotland, a clearly defined hierarchy of diocesan bishops and parochial structure for local churches, in line with the queen's experiences in Continental Europe, was developed.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] While some historians have discerned a decline of monasticism in the Late Middle Ages, the mendicant orders of friars grew, particularly in the expanding burghs, to meet the spiritual needs of the population.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] New saints and cults of religious devotion also proliferated.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The printing press also helped spread the "New Learning" known as Renaissance humanism, which was also embraced and spread by many Catholic clergy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The tradition of Crown-appointed "lay abbots" was reintroduced during the reign of James III of Scotland, with similar results to the time of the Celtic Church.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] King James V even appointed five of his illegitimate sons, with the assent of the Holy See, to the wealthiest abbacies in the Kingdom.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Similar critiques and calls also appear in the Middle Scots poetry of Makars William Dunbar and Robert Henryson.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Therefore, the Church in Scotland remained relatively strong and stable until the Scottish Reformation in the sixteenth century.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Scotland remained a Catholic country until the arrival of Protestant theology in books smuggled from abroad, beginning in the early 16th century.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] As often happens in cases of religious persecution of any kind, efforts by the Hierarchy of the Church to enforce the traditional principle of Canon law that "error has no rights" and treat Protestantism as a criminal offense triggered a widespread public backlash.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Particularly due to the greater availability and affordability of paper and books, the trials and executions of Protestant martyrs were widely publicized by the printing press and helped spread Protestantism even further.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In particular, after he was sentenced to death for his belief in Lutheranism following an Ecclesiastical trial presided over by Archbishop James Beaton and burned at the stake at St.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Andrews in 1528, it was said that the "reek [that is, smoke] of Master Patrick Hamilton infected as many as it blew upon".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Other similar cases had very similar results.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Despite also facing considerable popular opposition, the Scottish Reformation was effectively completed when the Scottish Parliament broke with the papacy and established a Calvinist confession by law in 1560.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] At that point, the offering or attending of the Mass was outlawed.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The subsequent suppression of monasteries, ban on religious orders, and, most particular, the iconoclasm and book burnings at monastic libraries that often accompanied them has recently been criticised, even by non-Catholic historians, as the destruction of Scotland's cultural inheritance.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Although illegal under the Papal Jurisdiction Act 1560 and other similar legislation, Scotland did not become "a theocratic state on the model of Calvin's Geneva", and an underground Catholic Church continued to survive and command the loyalty of at least half the population in Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In 1565, for example, John Knox relates that for one hour and four hours on two separate days underground priest Sir James Tarbet was tied to the Mercat Cross, Edinburgh and pelted with eggs after being caught saying the Tridentine Mass, which had been criminalised five years previously.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] James VI and his heirs, however, had intended for the Church of Scotland ("The Kirk") to embrace the Elizabethan religious settlement, High Church Anglicanism, Royal Supremacy, and episcopal polity.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] This led to long-term internal battles between Episcopalian and Presbyterian factions over control of the Kirk, the religious persecution of whichever faction had fallen from power, and the ultimate formation of a separate Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Persecution of Catholics, however, continued under both Episcopalian and Presbyterian governance.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Even so, the remaining domestic clergy played a relatively small role and the initiative was often left to lay leaders.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In these areas Catholic sacraments were administered by disguised and outlawed priests, but with relative openness.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Members of the nobility, who were often closely related, are believed to have been reluctant to pursue each other over matters of religious dissent.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] An English report in 1600 also alleged that a third of nobles and gentry were still Catholic in inclination.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] For example, in his efforts to enforce the King's religious settlement as Bishop of the Isles John Leslie sometimes ran into opposition from the local Scottish nobility (Scottish Gaelic: *flath*).
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] This was particularly true during the Bishop's efforts to shut down the illegal and underground pastoral work in his Diocese by Franciscan missionaries dispatched from the similarly underground Catholic Church in Ireland during the 1620s and '30s.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Patrick Hegarty, OFM, was arrested upon South Uist by a posse of priest hunters commanded in person by Bishop Leslie, but before the Bishop could deliver Fr.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The incident infuriated King Charles I, who sent a furious letter about it to Privy Council of Scotland on 10 December 1630 and was followed by unsuccessful efforts to summon the Highland nobleman to Inverary for criminal prosecution.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In most of Scotland, Catholicism became an underground faith in private households and secret parish communities, connected by ties of kinship.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] This reliance on the household meant that Scottish laywomen often became vitally important as the upholders and transmitters of the faith, such as in the case of Lady Fernihurst in the Borders.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] They transformed their households into centres of religious activity and created safe houses and secret chapels for priests.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The initiative was taken by a small group of Scots connected with the Crichton family, who had supplied the bishops of Dunkeld.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] They joined the Jesuit order and returned to attempt conversions.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The majority of surviving Scottish laity, however, were long ignored.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Some, including members of the Scottish nobility, converted openly to the Catholic Church despite the risks involved.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] For example, Banffshire aristocrat John Ogilvie (1569–1615) went on to be ordained a priest of the Society of Jesus in 1610.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] He was arrested by the Anglo-Catholic Archbishop of St.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Ogilvie, who was canonised by Pope Paul VI on 17 October 1976, is often assumed to be the only Scottish Catholic martyr of the Reformation era.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Nevertheless, the longevity of the Catholic Church's illegal status had a devastating impact on the numbers of the laity.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Even so, a significantly large Catholic population, served by outlawed "heather priests", continued to exist.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] This was especially the case in the Doric-speaking Northeast and the more remote Gàidhealtachd areas of the Hebrides, the Northwest Highlands, and in Galloway.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Numbers probably reduced in the seventeenth century and organisation deteriorated.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The Pope appointed Thomas Nicolson as the first Vicar Apostolic over the mission in 1694.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The country was organised into districts and by 1703 there were thirty-three Catholic clergy.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In 1733 it was divided into two vicariates, one for the Highland and one for the Lowland, each under a bishop.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In the Highland District, which had largely been looked after by Ulster Irish-speaking missionary priests, a minor seminary was founded by Bishop James Gordon to train native-born priests at Eilean Bàn in Loch Morar.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] It was moved in 1716 to Scalan in Glenlivet, which became the primary centre of underground education for Catholic priests in the area.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] It was illegal, and it was burned to the ground on several occasions by soldiers sent from beyond the Highlands.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Beyond Scalan there were six attempts to found a seminary in the Highlands between 1732 and 1838, all suffering both financially and due to Catholicism's illegal status.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Clergy entered the country secretly and although services were illegal they were maintained.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Even though many Presbyterians and Episcopalians also fought as Jacobites, aftermath of the Jacobite rising of 1745 further increased the persecution faced by Catholics in Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The repression was particularly intense during (Scottish Gaelic: *Bliadhna nan Creach* lit.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] "the year of the pillaging") that followed the defeat of the Jacobite Army at the Battle of Culloden.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] 3, against Jesuits and Catholic priests.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Also according to Bishop John Geddes, "Early in the spring of 1746, some ships of war came to the coast of the isle of Barra and landed some men, who threatened they would lay desolate the whole island if the priest was not delivered up to them.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Father James Grant, who was missionary then, and afterward Bishop, being informed of the threats in a safe retreat in which he was in a little island, surrendered himself, and was carried prisoner to Mingarry Castle on the Western coast (i.e.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] After long and cruel imprisonment with other Catholic priests at Inverness Gaol and in a prison hulk anchored in the River Thames, Grant was deported to the Netherlands and warned never to return to the British Isles.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Like the other priests deported with him, Fr.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Grant returned to Scotland almost immediately.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] His fellow prisoner, Father Alexander Cameron, an outlawed "heather priest" to Clan Fraser of Lovat and Clan Chisholm, former military chaplain, and the younger brother to Donald Cameron of Lochiel, the Chief of Clan Cameron, was less fortunate.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Cameron died aboard the prison hulk due to the hardship of his imprisonment on 19 October 1746.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] During the 21st century, the Knights of St.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Columba at the University of Glasgow launched a campaign to canonize Fr.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Cameron, "with the hope that he will become a great saint for Scotland and that our nation will merit from his intercession." They erected a small petition book at their altar of St.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Joseph in the University Catholic Chapel, Turnbull Hall.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] It is one of the necessary prerequisites for Canonisation in the Catholic Church that there is a cult of devotion to the saint.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] According to historian Daniel Szechi, however, the government's post-Culloden backlash focused upon the Catholic clergy and laity of the Highland District, while leaving the much larger and better organized Lowland District reasonably unscathed.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] According to Marcus Tanner, "As the Reformed Church faltered in the urban and increasingly industrialised Lowlands, Presbyterianism made its great breakthrough among the Gaelic Highlanders, virtually snapping cultural bonds that had linked them to Ireland since the lordship of Dalriada.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The Highlands, outside tiny Catholic enclaves like in South Uist and Barra, took on the contours they have since preserved - a region marked by a strong tradition of sabbatarianism and a puritanical distaste for instrumental music and dancing, which have only recently regained popular acceptance".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The pioneering Victorian era folklorist and Celticist John Francis Campbell of Islay (Scottish Gaelic: *Iain Òg Ìle*) and his many assistant collectors had very different reasons for criticising what they saw as the unnecessary excesses of the Calvinisation of the Highlands and Islands.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Exact numbers of communicants are uncertain, given the illegal status of Catholicism.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In 1755 it was estimated that there were some 16,500 communicants, mainly in the north and west.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In 1764, "the total Catholic population in Scotland would have been about 33,000 or 2.6% of the total population.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Of these 23,000 were in the Highlands." Another estimate for 1764 is of 13,166 Catholics in the Highlands, perhaps a quarter of whom had emigrated by 1790, and another source estimates Catholics as perhaps 10% of the population.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Few Highland ministers emulated the Catholic clergy of Ireland, who commandeered the Repeal movement in the 1830s and 1840s and the land campaigns several decades on.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The Catholic clergy in agitated Irish counties like Tipperary led the agrarian militants from the front, which cannot be said for most Disruption clergy or their successors.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Evangelical Presbyterianism counseled submission and acceptance of misfortune.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] While most of the landlords responsible for the Highland Clearances did not target people for ethnic or religious reasons, there is evidence of anti-Catholicism among some of them.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In particular, large numbers of Catholics emigrated from the Western Highlands in the period 1770 to 1810 and there is evidence that anti Catholic sentiment (along with famine, poverty, and rackrenting) was a contributory factor in that period.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In an April 1787 letter from Moidart to the Congregation for Propaganda in Rome, Fr.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Austin MacDonald wrote, "On account of the emigration of the people of Knoydart to Canada, along with their priest; it fell to me in the autumn to attend to those who were left behind, and during the winter to the people of Moydart (sic) as well.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Although not less than 600 Catholics went to America, still I administered the Sacraments to over 500 souls who remained.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In Glengarry County, Upper Canada, a Canadian Gaelic-speaking pioneer settlement was established for Scottish Catholics through the efforts of British Army military chaplain and future Catholic bishop Alexander Macdonnell.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] The settlement's inhabitants consisted of members of the Glengarry Fencibles, a disbanded Catholic unit of the Highland Fencible Corps, and their families.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In 1879, a visitor from Scotland enthusiastically declared that the Glengarry dialect of Scottish Gaelic was better preserved, "with the most perfect accent, and with scarcely any, if any, admixture of English", in Glengarry County and in Cornwall, Ontario than in Lochaber itself.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] For very similar reasons, Odo Blundell commented ruefully in 1909 that the language, customs, and oral tradition of once densely populated and overwhelmingly Catholic Strathglass were better preserved in Nova Scotia than in Scotland.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] After receiving his post following the 1878 Restoration of the Hierarchy and during the last decade of the Clearances, Bishop Angus MacDonald of the Diocese of Argyll and the Isles led by example during the height of the Highland Land League agitation.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Roger Hutchinson further writes that Bishop MacDonald's choice to assign Gaelic-speaking priests from the Scottish mainland to parishes in the Hebrides was accordingly no accident.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] About that time, when the Bishop and his priests were the leaders of direct action, rent strikes, and other acts of resistance to the Anglo-Scottish landlords, Fr.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Initially, clergymen from the recusant districts of North-East Scotland played an important part in providing support.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In Dumbarton, which in 1820 only had two or three Catholic families, the population was increased by Irish and Highland migration until the first parish church, dedicated to St Patrick, was built in 1830.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] MacPhail, "Before 1830, a few Catholics used to meet in the ruins of the old pre-Reformation parish church of Cardross in the Levengrove policies and later, just before their church was built, the Rev.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] John Gordon of Greenock held services in an old store in College Street.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] In 1837, it was estimated that there were 284 Catholics in Dumbarton".
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] A very similar riot had previously been incited by Orr, whom Tim Pat Coogan has compared to the Rev.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Ian Paisley, in Greenock on 12 July 1851.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] When Orr was thrown into prison, his followers *also* rioted.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Attempts were also made to convert Irish migrants to Presbyterianism by recruiting missionaries like Rev.
[src:catholic-church-in-scotland/catholic-church-in-scotland-p01] Patrick MacMenemy, a native speaker of Ulster Irish from the Glens of Antrim, but whose ministerial reputation collapsed following allegations of womanizing in 1885.
